Author: Marie Lu
My Review: 3.5 stars. This book is fast-paced with compelling characters. Marie Lu's writing style is definitely up my alley, crisp and articulate, which made my reading experience more enjoyable. This installment explores more on the political aspect of the setting yet still manages to make it action-packed. The ending though *SCREECH* !! There are minors parts in the story where I feel confused or 'meh' about, mostly on the plot, but maybe it's just my pea sized brain refusing to establish rapport with me at 4 am while trying to finish reading this book.

My Review: 3.5 stars. This book is sweet and fluffy like a mochi and is so heartwarming. I somehow relate to Kimi in terms of not knowing where my passion lies and fantasizing things. Title: From Blood and Ash (Blood and Ash, #1)
Author: Jennifer L. Armentrout
My Review:
disclaimer: I apologise for my lack of words for I am not feeling articulate while writing this review.

I read this with no expectations at all and I must say, what the hell did I just read?? the world building is so intriguing even though I am not a fan of werewolves and vampires. The "plot twists" even though I already know what is coming, I still felt surprised regardless. The amount of steamy scenes made me scream so much. The amount of times I gasped while reading this book is immeasurable. Overall, this is a wholeass journey.

Title: Stalking Jack the Ripper (Stalking Jack the Ripper, #1)
Author: Kerri Maniscalco
My Review: This is my first time reading 'horror' and i am pleasantly surprised that I liked this book. I adored the two main protagonists— Audrey Rose Wadsworth and Thomas Cresswell. I really found Cresswell endearing and the flirtatious banters between the two characters are making me blush profusely. In terms of the plot itself, it was fine. The 'horror' level is only at its minimum so I found myself very immersed in the story and I enjoyed it without getting terrified. Over all, I find this book enjoyable though it's not too astounding to make me rate it five stars.

My Review: i thought there won't be anything superior to the 'enemies to lovers' trope but this 'lovers to enemies to lovers' trope? god tier. my romance loving ass really enjoyed this book but what really made me even like this novel is the writing. five stars well deserved and i am expecting more books to read from this author in the future.

Title: Red, White & Royal Blue
Author: Casey McQuiston
My Review: Added to my favorite reads in 2020 because it was damn good. This magnificent of a prose made me feel an abundance of overwhelming emotions. I laughed a lot (and when I say a lot, I meant A LOT) , I giggled loudly that my neighbours are probably complaining about me, and I shed tears because of this goddamn book. This story has a lot of lovable characters. The representation is truly commendable and the writing is humorous and comprehensive. I love every part of this book. I thank the skies for letting me pick up this beautiful masterpiece and I thank the author for writing such an excellent book. I cannot wait to read this again.

Title: Anne of Green Gables (Anne of Green Gables, #1)
Author: L.M. Montgomery
My Review:
This book is exquisite that I literally cried after finishing this. I love Anne's character development and how she learns from every mistakes she make. I also love that even though Anne isn't what Marilla and Matthew wanted at first, as time passed, they learned to love her so deeply. I must say that the friendship and the a teeny tiny bit of love are truly wonderful. (ehem Mr. Gilbert Blythe) Diana and Anne's friendship makes me wonder how things are different from their time to the current century. I cried when Matthew became deceased even though I already expected it to be (I read the summary in my Filipino textbook). I felt Anne's despair because of it.
Overall, it was a wonderful story with a beautiful writing so I will certainly give it a five out of five.
